task.p:
If  \uvec{v} = 5 \uvec{u}_1 + 3 \uvec{u}_2 + (-1)\uvec{u}_3 ,
then

	\matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B}
	= \begin{bmatrix}  \\  \\  \end{bmatrix}
.

introduction.p:
Once again, suppose V is a three-dimensional vector space,
we have a basis
 \basisfont{B} = \{ \uvec{u}_1, \uvec{u}_2, \uvec{u}_3 \} 
for V,
and \uvec{w} is a vector in V for which we know the coordinate vector relative to \basisfont{B},
 \matrixOf{\uvec{w}}{B} = \left[\begin{array}{r} 5 \\ 3 \\ -1 \end{array}\right] .

postlude.p:
Notationally, the conversion process can be written

	\ucobmtrx{B}{B'} \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B} = \matrixOf{\uvec{v}}{B'}
.

introduction.p:
Here are two bases of \matrixring_2(\R), the standard basis

	\basisfont{S} = \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
,
and another basis

	\basisfont{B} = \left\{
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 2 \amp 1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 2 \\ 1 \amp 0 \end{bmatrix},
		\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
	\right\}
.
